# The comm Command:
# -----------------

    -> The comm command in Linux is used to compare two sorted files line by line. 
    
    -> It displays:

        Lines unique to the first file
        Lines unique to the second file
        Lines common to both files

    -> It is useful for:

        Comparing text files
        Identifying common records
        Finding differences between datasets

    -> Syntax:

        # com [options] file1 file2
    
        *** Important: Both files must be sorted before using comm.

    -> Common Options:

        Option|	Description
        ------|  -----------
              |
        -1	  |  Suppress column 1
        -2	  |  Suppress column 2
        -3	  |  Suppress column 3

    -> Show only common lines:

        # comm -12 file1 file2

    -> Show lines only from first file:

        # comm -23 file1 file2
    
    -> Show lines only from second file:

        # comm -13 file1 file2

    -> Difference Between comm and diff:

        Feature	                comm	diff
        ------------------------------------

        Requires sorted files	Yes	    No
        Line-by-line comparison	Yes	    Yes
        Shows detailed changes  No	    Yes
        Simpler output	        Yes	    No

    -> Summary

        The comm command is used to compare two sorted files and identify:

            Unique lines in each file
            Common lines between files

        It is especially useful for:

            File comparison
            Data analysis
            User/account comparison
            Log analysis
            Record verification
